.SS Description
\f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] control panel for external Visual Display Units
(VDUs, monitors, displays).
It supports displays connected via DisplayPort, DVI, HDMI, USB, and
built\-in laptop\-panels.
Out of the box, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] offers a subset of controls
including brightness, contrast and audio controls.
Additional controls can be enabled via the *Settings\-Dialog**.
.PP
\f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] interacts with VDUs by using \f[B]ddcutil\f[R] to
issue standard VESA \f[I]Virtual Control Panel\f[R] (\f[I]VCP\f[R])
commands via the VESA \f[I]Display Data Channel\f[R] (\f[I]DDC\f[R]).
\f[B]Ddcutil\f[R] provides a robust interface that is tolerant of the
vagaries of the many OEM DDC implementations.
.PP
From \f[B]vdu_controls 2.0\f[R] onward, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] defaults
to using the \f[B]D\-Bus ddcutil\-service\f[R].
Should the \f[B]ddcutil\-service\f[R] be unavailable,
\f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will fall back to running the \f[B]ddcutil\f[R]
command to perform each request.
.PP
The UI look\-and\-feel dynamically adjusts to dark and light themes.
The application may optionally run in the system tray of KDE, Deepin,
GNOME, and Xfce (and possibly others).
For desktops that don\(cqt integrate with Qt/KDE theming, the
\f[B]qt5ct\f[R] and \f[B]qt6ct\f[R] utilities may be used to alter the
overall Qt theme.
.PP
The UI provides an optional \f[I]ambient\-light slider\f[R] for
simultaneously adjusting all VDUs according to custom per\-VDU ambient
lux/brightness profiles.
Options are included for semi\-automatic adjustment proportional to
daylight at a given geographic location, or fully automatic adjustment
by accessing hardware light\-meters, webcams, or other devices.
.PP
Named \f[I]Preset\f[R] configurations can be saved and recalled.
For example, presets may be created for night, day, photography, movies,
and so forth.
Presets can be triggered by specific ambient light levels, scheduled
according to local solar elevation, vetoed by local weather conditions,
or activated by UNIX signals.
.PP
From any UI window, \f[B]F1\f[R] accesses help, and \f[B]F10\f[R]
accesses the \f[I]main\-menu\f[R].
The \f[I]main\-menu\f[R] is also available via the hamburger\-menu, and
also via the right\-mouse button in either the main\-window or the
system\-tray icon.
The \f[I]main\-menu\f[R] has \f[B]ALT\-key\f[R] shortcuts for all menu
items (subject to sufficient letters being available to distinguish all
user defined presets).
.PP
For further information, including screenshots, see
https://github.com/digitaltrails/vdu_controls .
.PP
The long\-term effects of repeatably rewriting a VDUs setting are not
well understood, but some concerns have been expressed.
See \f[B]LIMITATIONS\f[R] for further details.
.SS Configuration
Configuration changes can be made via the \f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R] or
by editing the config\-files.
.SS Settings Menu and Config files
The \f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R] features a tab for editing common/default
settings as well as tabs specific to each VDU.
The config files are named according to the following scheme:
.IP \(bu 2
Application wide default config:
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/vdu_controls.conf\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
VDU model and serial number config:
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/<model>_<serial|display_num>.conf\f[R]
.IP \(bu 2
VDU model\-only config:
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/<model>.conf\f[R] (deprecated, no longer
created).
.PP
The VDU\-specific config files can be used to:
.IP \(bu 2
Correct manufacturer built\-in metadata.
.IP \(bu 2
Customize which controls are to be provided for each VDU.
.IP \(bu 2
Define a user\-friendly label for each VDU.
.IP \(bu 2
Set optimal \f[B]ddcutil\f[R] DDC parameters for each VDU.
.PP
The config files are in INI\-format divided into a number of sections as
outlined below::
.IP
.EX
[vdu\-controls\-globals]
# The vdu\-controls\-globals section is only required in $HOME/.config/vdu_controls/vdu_controls.conf
system\-tray\-enabled = yes|no
splash\-screen\-enabled = yes|no
translations\-enabled = yes|no
weather\-enabled = yes|no
schedule\-enabled = yes|no
lux\-options\-enabled = yes|no
warnings\-enabled = yes|no
debug\-enabled = yes|no
syslog\-enabled = yes|no

[vdu\-controls\-widgets]
# Yes/no for each of the control options that vdu_controls normally provides by default.
brightness = yes|no
contrast = yes|no
audio\-volume = yes|no
audio\-mute = yes|no
audio\-treble = yes|no
audio\-bass = yes|no
audio\-mic\-volume = yes|no
input\-source = yes|no
power\-mode = yes|no
osd\-language = yes|no

# Enable ddcutil supported codes not enabled in vdu_controls by default, CSV list of two\-digit hex values.
enable\-vcp\-codes = NN, NN, NN

# User friendly VDU name
vdu_name = My Main Monitor (on the right)

[ddcutil\-parameters]
# Useful values appear to be >=0.1
sleep\-multiplier = 0.5

[ddcutil\-capabilities]
# The (possibly edited) output from \(dqddcutil \-\-display N capabilities\(dq with leading spaces retained.
capabilities\-override =
.EE
.PP
Config files can only be used to enable and alter definitions of VCP
codes supported by \f[B]ddcutil\f[R].
Unsupported manufacturer\-specific features should only be enabled with
caution; some may have irreversible consequences, including bricking the
hardware.
.PP
As well as using the \f[B]Settings\f[R], config files may also be
created by the command line option::
.IP
.EX
vdu_controls \-\-create\-config\-files
.EE
.PP
which will create initial templates based on the currently connected
VDUs.
.PP
The config files are completely optional, they need not be used if the
default options are found to be adequate.
.SS Adding value restrictions to a VDU\(cqs capabilities override
In some cases, a VDU\(cqs DDC reported minimums and maximums may be
incorrect or overstated.
Within vdu_controls this can be corrected by overriding the DDC reported
range.
For example, perhaps a VDU reports it supports a brightness range of 0
to 100, but in fact only practically supports 20 to 90.
This can be corrected by bringing up the VDU\(cqs settings tab and
editing the text in the \f[B]capabilities override\f[R]:
.IP "1." 3
Open the \f[I]Settings\f[R] tab for the VDU, navigate to the
\f[I]capabilities override\f[R] field
.IP "2." 3
locate the feature, in this example, the brightness,
.IP "3." 3
add a \f[B]Values:\f[R] \f[B]min..max\f[R] specification to the line
following the feature definition,
.IP "4." 3
save the changes.
.PP
For the brightness example, the completed edit would look like::
.IP
.EX
Feature: 10 (Brightness)
    Values: 20..80
.EE
.PP
The vdu_controls slider for that value will now be restricted to the
specified range.
.SS Adding a refresh/reload requirement to a VDU\(cqs capabilities override
Altering the values of some VCP codes may result in a cascade of changes
to other codes.
For example, changing a VCP value for \f[I]Picture Mode\f[R] might
result in changes to several VCP\-code features, including brightness,
contrast, and others.
Exactly which codes have these kinds of side effects isn\(cqt indicated
in the metadata obtained from each VDU, however, vdu_controls supports
adding \f[I]refresh\f[R] annotations to the feature\-names within the
\f[B]capabilities override\f[R].
For example::
.IP
.EX
Feature: 15 (Picture Mode)
.EE
.PP
Can be annotated with::
.IP
.EX
Feature: 15 (Picture Mode *refresh*)
.EE
.PP
With this annotation, when ever \f[I]Picture Mode\f[R] is altered,
vdu_controls will reload all configuration files and refresh all control
values from the VDUs.
.SS DBUS ddcutil\-service
When available, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] defaults to interacting with VDUs
via the DBUS \f[B]ddcutil\-service\f[R] service rather than the
\f[B]ddcutil\f[R] command.
With some older monitors, the \f[B]ddcutil\f[R] command can take a
couple of seconds to handshake a connection each time it is run.
The service caches connections and should be both faster and more
reliable than the command.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Whether to use the service can be controlled by the \f[B]DBUS
client\f[R] checkbox in the \f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R].
.PP
\f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] can use the service to monitor for DPMS events
and VDU connectivity events, including power\-cycling VDUs or
hot\-plugging cable connections.
The reliability and timeliness of event detection can vary depending on
the hardware involved (GPU model, GPU driver, VDU model, and type of
connector\-cable).
In some cases, the service polling for DPMS or connection status may
wake some VDU models.
Both \f[B]ddcutil\-service\f[R] or \f[B]libddcutil\f[R] offer options
for finer control over which events are detected and how.
Whether to enable events in \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] is controlled by the
\f[B]DBUS events\f[R] checkbox in the \f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R].
.SS Laptop\-Panel brightness control
Starting with version 2.6, laptop panels are supported for
brightness\-only control.
When laptop support is enabled, the widely available command line
utility \f[B]brightnessctl\f[R] is used to emulate DDC control of
brightness (https://github.com/Hummer12007/brightnessctl).
Additionally, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will react to laptop
brightness\-function\-keys or inactivity\-dimming by using the
\f[B]python3\-pyudev\f[R] library to monitor udev for
\f[I]brightness\f[R] events.
.SS DDC emulation for special cases
The \f[B]ddcutil\-emulator\f[R] option is provided for handling special
cases.
When set, it will be run in addition to the normal DDC sources.
It can be used to add brightness controls and other controls for
non\-DDC devices.
For example, you might add a brightness control for a
keyboard\-backlight, or for case\-LED\(cqs.
To use it you would have to create a script that emulates the basic
\f[B]ddcutil\f[R] command set (see included sample script).
.SS Presets
A named \f[I]Preset\f[R] can be used to save the current VDU settings
for later recall.
Any number of presets can be created for different lighting conditions
or different applications, for example, \f[I]Night\f[R], \f[I]Day\f[R],
\f[I]Overcast\f[R], \f[I]Sunny\f[R], \f[I]Photography\f[R], and
\f[I]Video\f[R].
Each preset can be assigned a name and icon.
.PP
The \f[I]Presets\f[R] item in \f[I]main\-menu\f[R] will bring up a
\f[I]Presets\-Dialog\f[R] for managing and applying presets.
The \f[I]main\-menu\f[R] also includes an item for each existing preset.
.PP
Any small SVG or PNG can be assigned as a preset\(cqs icon.
Monochrome SVG icons that conform to the Plasma color conventions will
be automatically inverted if the desktop them is changed from dark to
light.
If a preset lacks an icon, an icon will be created from the initials of
the first and last words of its name.
A starter set of icons is included in
\f[B]/usr/share/vdu_controls/icons/\f[R].
.PP
Any time the current VDUs settings match those of a preset, the
preset\(cqs name and icon will automatically show in the window\-title,
tray tooltip, tray icon.
.PP
Each preset is stored in config directory as:
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/Preset_<preset_name>.conf\f[R]
.PP
Preset files are saved in INI\-file format for ease of editing.
Each preset file contains a section for each connected VDU, for
example::
.IP
.EX
[preset]
icon = /usr/share/icons/breeze/status/16/cloudstatus.svg
solar\-elevation = eastern\-sky 40
transition\-type = none

[HP_ZR24w_CNT008]
brightness = 50
osd\-language = 02

[LG_HDR_4K_89765]
brightness = 13
audio\-speaker\-volume = 16
.EE
.PP
When creating a preset file, you may select which controls to save for
each VDU.
For example, you might create a preset that includes the brightness, but
not the contrast or audio\-volume.
.PP
While using the GUI to create or edit a preset, other automated
adjustments are blocked until editing is complete.
.SS Presets \- VDU initialization\-presets
For a VDU named \f[B]abc\f[R] with a serial number \f[B]xyz\f[R], if a
preset named \f[B]abx xyz\f[R] exists, that preset will be restored at
startup or when ever the VDU is subsequently detected.
.PP
This feature is designed to restore settings that cannot be saved in the
VDU\(cqs NVRAM or for VDUs where the NVRAM capacity has been exhausted
or is faulty.
.SS Presets \- solar elevation triggers
A preset may be set to automatically trigger when the sun rises to a
specified elevation.
The idea is to allow a preset to trigger relative to dawn or dusk, or
when the sun rises above some surrounding terrain (the time of which
will vary as the seasons change).
.PP
If a preset has an elevation, the preset will be triggered each day at a
time calculated according to the latitude and longitude specified by in
the \f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R] \f[I]location\f[R] option.
By choosing an appropriate \f[I]solar\-elevation\f[R] a preset may be
confined to specific times of the year.
For example, a preset with a positive solar elevation will not trigger
at mid\-winter in the Arctic circle (because the sun never gets that
high).
Any preset may be manually invoked regardless of its specified solar
elevations.
.PP
To assign a trigger, use the \f[I]Presets\-Dialog\f[R] to set a
preset\(cqs \f[I]solar\-elevation\f[R].
A solar elevation may range from \-19 degrees in the eastern sky
(morning/ascending) to \-19 degrees in the western sky
(afternoon/descending), with a maximum nearing 90 degrees at midday.
.PP
On any given day, the \f[I]Presets\-Dialog\f[R] may be used to
temporarily override any trigger, in which case the trigger is suspended
until the following day.
For example, a user might choose to disable a trigger intended for the
brightest part of the day if the day is particularly dull.
.PP
At startup \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will restore the most recent preset
that would have been triggered for this day (if any).
For example, say a user has \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] set to run at login,
and they\(cqve also set a preset to trigger at dawn, but they don\(cqt
log in until just after dawn, the overdue dawn preset will be triggered
at login.
.SS Presets \- time\-of\-day triggers
A preset may be set to trigger at a fixed time each day.
This is an alternative to the elevation trigger.
It\(cqs not possible for a single preset to have both kinds of trigger.
.PP
As with the elevation trigger, the \f[I]Presets\-Dialog\f[R] may be used
to temporarily override any trigger, in which case the trigger is
suspended until the following day.
Similarly, at startup, the most recent preset that would have been
triggered for this day will be restored.
.SS Presets \- Smooth Transitions
\f[B]To minimize writes to VDU NVRAM, stepped smooth\-transitions have
been deprecated and are disabled for version 2.6.5 onward.\f[R]
.SS Presets \- supplementary weather requirements
A solar elevation trigger can have a weather requirement which will be
checked against the weather reported by https://wttr.in.
.PP
By default, there are three possible weather requirements:
\f[B]good\f[R], \f[B]bad\f[R], and \f[B]all weather\f[R].
Each requirement is defined by a file containing a list of WWO
(https://www.worldweatheronline.com) weather codes, one per line.
The three default requirements are contained in the files
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/{good,bad,all}.weather\f[R].
Additional weather requirements can be created by using a text editor to
create further files.
The \f[B]all.weather\f[R] file exists primarily as a convenient resource
that lists all possible codes.
.PP
Because reported current weather conditions may be inaccurate or out of
date, it\(cqs best to use weather requirements as a coarse measure.
Going beyond good and bad may not be very practical.
What\(cqs possible might depend on your local weather conditions.
.PP
To ensure \f[B]wttr.in\f[R] supplies the weather for your location,
please ensure that \f[B]Settings\f[R] \f[B]Location\f[R] includes a
place\-name suffix.
The \f[B]Settings\f[R] \f[B]Location\f[R] \f[B]Detect\f[R] button has
been enhanced to fill out a place\-name for you.
Should \f[B]wttr.in\f[R] not recognize a place\-name, the place\-name
can be manually edited to something more suitable.
The nearest big city or an airport\-code will do, for example: LHR, LAX,
JFK.
You can use a web browser to test a place\-name, for example:
https://wttr.in/JFK
.PP
When weather requirements are in use, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will check
that the coordinates in \f[B]Settings\f[R] \f[B]Location\f[R] are a
reasonable match for those returned from \f[B]wttr.in\f[R], a warning
will be issued if they are more than 200 km (124 miles) apart.
.PP
If the place\-name is left blank, the \f[B]wttr.in\f[R] server will try
to guess your location from your external IP address.
The guess may not be accurate and may vary over time.
.SS Presets \- remote control
UNIX/Linux signals may be used to cause \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] to
restore a preset or to initiate a refresh of the application from the
connected monitors.
Signals in the range 40 to 55 correspond to first to last presets (if
any are defined).
Additionally, SIGHUP can be used to initiate \(lqRefresh settings from
monitors\(rq.
For example:
.IP
.EX
Identify the running vdu_controls (assuming it is installed as /usr/bin/vdu_controls)::

    ps axwww | grep \(aq[/]usr/bin/vdu_controls\(aq

Combine this with kill to trigger a preset change::

    kill \-40 $(ps axwww | grep \(aq[/]usr/bin/vdu_controls\(aq | awk \(aq{print $1}\(aq)
    kill \-41 $(ps axwww | grep \(aq[/]usr/bin/vdu_controls\(aq | awk \(aq{print $1}\(aq)

If some other activity has changed a VDU\(aqs settings, trigger vdu_controls to update its UI::

    kill \-HUP $(ps axwww | grep \(aq[/]usr/bin/vdu_controls\(aq | awk \(aq{print $1}\(aq)
.EE
.PP
Any other signals will be handled normally (in many cases they will
result in process termination).
.SS Ambient Light Levels and Light/Lux Metering
The default UI includes an \f[B]ambient\-light slider\f[R] which will
simultaneously adjust all VDUs according to custom VDU profiles.
As well as manual adjustment, the slider\-value can adjust
semi\-automatically based on geolocation and local\-datetime, or
fully\-automatically by hardware light\-metering.
.PP
The \f[B]Light\-Metering\f[R] dialog provides options for setting up
light\-metering, adjustment intervals, and per\-VDU lux/brightness
profiles.
The metering dialog additionally provides a rolling display of current
metered light level and VDU brightness levels.
.PP
\f[B]Semi\-automatic ambient\-light level adjustment\f[R] periodically
adjusts the light\-level in proportion to the estimated sunlight for
your geolocation.
Use the ambient\-light\-level slider to indicate your current lighting
condition.
This establishes a baseline from which the application will periodically
reestimate your ambient\-light\-level in proportion to the estimated
sunlight for your location.
If conditions change, adjust the slider to alter the baseline
proportion.
The estimated trajectory is plotted in the \f[I]Light\-Metering
dialog\f[R], along with the \f[I]Estimate of outdoor lux\f[R]
(\f[B]Eo\f[R]) and the \f[I]Daylight\-Factor\f[R] (\f[B]DF\f[R]) \- the
baseline ratio of indoor to outdoor lux.
.PP
\f[B]Fully\-automatic ambient\-light level adjustment\f[R] requires
setting up a hardware lux metering device.
A metering device may be a serial\-device, a UNIX FIFO (named\-pipe), or
an executable (script or program):
.IP \(bu 2
A serial\-device must periodically supply one floating\-point lux\-value
terminated by a carriage\-return newline.
.IP \(bu 2
A FIFO must periodically supply one floating\-point lux\-value
terminated by a newline.
.IP \(bu 2
An executable must supply one floating\-point lux\-value reading
terminated by a newline each time it is run.
.PP
Possible hardware devices include:
.IP \(bu 2
An Arduino with a GY\-30/BH1750 lux meter writing to a usb serial\-port.
.IP \(bu 2
A webcam periodically sampled to produce approximate lux values.
Values might be estimated by analyzing image content or image settings
that contribute to exposure, such as ISO values, apertures, and shutter
speed.
.PP
Further information on various lux metering options, as well as
instructions for constructing and programming an Arduino with a
GY\-30/BH1750, can be found at:
.IP
.EX
https://github.com/digitaltrails/vdu_controls/blob/master/Lux\-metering.md
.EE
.PP
Example scripts for mapping a webcam\(cqs average\-brightness to
approximate lux values are included in
\f[B]/usr/share/vdu_controls/sample\-scripts/\f[R], or they can also be
downloaded from the following location:
.IP
.EX
https://github.com/digitaltrails/vdu_controls/tree/master/sample\-scripts.
.EE
.PP
The examples include \f[B]vlux_meter.py\f[R], a beta\-release Qt\-GUI
python\-script that meters from a webcam and writes to a FIFO
(\f[B]$HOME/.cache/vlux_fifo\f[R]).
Controls are included for mapping image\-brightness to lux mappings, and
for defining a crop from which to sample brightness values.
The script optionally runs in the system\-tray.
.PP
The examples may require customizing for your own webcam and lighting
conditions.
.PP
If ambient light level controls are not required, the
\f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R] includes an option to disable and hide them.
.SS Lux Metering and brightness adjustments
The auto\-brightness adjustment feature includes several measures to
reduce the number of changes passed to the VDU:
.IP \(bu 2
Lux/Brightness Profiles may be altered for local conditions so that
brightness levels remain constant over set ranges of lux values (night,
day, and so forth).
.IP \(bu 2
Adjustments are only made at intervals of one or more minutes (default
is 10 minutes).
.IP \(bu 2
The adjustment task passes lux values through a smoothing low\-pass
filter.
.IP \(bu 2
When a VDU brightness profile is set to interpolate, changes specified
by the curve will only be applied when they cross a minimum threshold
(default 10%).
.IP \(bu 2
A VDU brightness profile may be set to stair\-step with no interpolation
of intermediate values.
.PP
When ambient light conditions are fluctuating, for example, due to
passing clouds, automatic adjust can be manually suspended.
The main\-panel, \f[I]main\-menu\f[R], and light\-metering dialog each
contain controls for toggling Auto/Manual.
Additionally, moving the manual lux\-slider turns off automatic
adjustment.
.PP
The Light\-metering dialog includes an option to enable auto\-brightness
interpolation.
This option will enable the calculation of values between steps in the
profiles.
To avoid small fluctuating changes, interpolation won\(cqt result in
brightness changes less than 10%.
During interpolation, if a lux value is found to be close to any
attached\-preset, the preset values will be preferred over interpolated
ones.
.SS Saving a Daylight\-Factor in a Preset
The Preset\-Dialog allows a Daylight\-Factor to be manually entered and
saved as part of a Preset.
A Preset can be created to save only the Daylight Factor and nothing
else.
This provides a way to save and recall favourite Daylight\-Factors for
use with semi\-automatic brightness adjustment.
.SS Light/Lux Metering and Triggering Presets
The Light\-Metering Dialog includes the ability to set a Preset to
trigger at a lux value.
This feature is accessed by hovering under the bottom axis of the Lux
Profile Chart.
.PP
When a preset is attached to a lux value, the preset\(cqs brightness
values become fixed points on the Lux Profile Chart.
When the specified metered lux value is achieved, the stepping process
will restore the preset\(cqs brightness values and then trigger the full
restoration of the preset.
This ordering of events reduces the likelihood of metered\-stepping and
preset\-restoration from clashing.
.PP
A preset that does not include a VDU\(cqs brightness may be attached to
a lux point to restore one or more non\-brightness controls.
For example, on reaching a particular lux level, an attached preset
might restore a contrast setting.
.PP
If a preset is attached to a lux value and then detached, the
preset\(cqs profile points will be converted to normal (editable)
profile points.
Attach/detach is a quick way to copy VDU brightness values from presets
if you don\(cqt want to permanently attach them.
.PP
If you use light\-metered auto\-brightness and preset\-scheduling
together, their combined effects may conflict.
For example, a scheduled preset may set a reduced brightness, but soon
after, light\-metering might increase it.
If you wish to use the two together, design your lux/brightness profile
steps to match the brightness levels of specific presets.
For example, give a full\-sun preset and a corresponding step in a
lux/brightness Profile the same brightness value.
.SS Lux Metering Internal Parameters
The following internal constants can be altered by manually editing
\f[B]\(ti/.config/vdu_controls/AutoLux.conf\f[R].
They guide the various metering and auto\-adjustment heuristics::
.IP
.EX
  [lux\-meter]
  # How many times per minute to sample from the Lux meter (for auto\-adjustment)
  samples\-per\-minute=3
  # How many samples to include in the smoothing process
  smoother\-n=5
  # How heavily should past values smooth the present value (smaller = more smoothing)
  # See: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low\-pass_filter#Simple_infinite_impulse_response_filter
  smoother\-alpha=0.5
  # If an interpolated value yields a change in brightness, how big should the change
  # be to trigger an actual VDU change in brightness? Also determines how close
  # an interpolated value needs to be to an attached preset\(aqs brightness in order
  # to prefer triggering the preset over applying the interpolated value.
  interpolation\-sensitivity\-percent=10
.EE
.SS Improving Response Time: Dynamic Optimization and Sleep Multipliers
If you are using \f[B]ddcutil\f[R] version 2.0 or greater,
\f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will default to using the \f[B]ddcutil\f[R]
\f[I]dynamic sleep optimizer\f[R].
The optimizer automatically tunes and caches VDU specific timings when
ever \f[B]ddcutil\f[R] is run.
Any reliability\-issues or errors may be automatically resolved as the
optimizer refines its cached timings.
Should problems persist, the optimizer can be disabled by adding
\f[B]\-\-disable\-dynamic\-sleep\f[R] to the \f[I]ddcutil extra
arguments\f[R] in the \f[I]Settings\-Dialog\f[R] (either globally on the
\f[I]vdu_controls tab\f[R] or selectively under each VDU\(cqs tab).
If dynamic sleep is disabled, multipliers can then be manually assigned.
The optimizer\(cqs heuristics continue to be refined, it may be that
some issues may be resolved by moving to a more recent version of
\f[B]libddcutil/ddcutil\f[R].
.PP
For versions of \f[B]ddcutil\f[R] prior to 2.0, you can manually set the
\f[B]vdu_control\f[R] \f[B]sleep\-multiplier\f[R] passed to
\f[B]ddcutil\f[R].
A sleep multiplier less than one will speed up the i2c protocol
interactions at the risk of increased protocol errors.
The default sleep multiplier of 1.0 has to be quite conservative, many
VDUs can cope with smaller multipliers.
A bit of experimentation with multiplier values may greatly speed up
responsiveness.
In a multi\-VDU setup, individual sleep multipliers can be configured.
.SS Improving Response Time and Reliability: Connections and Controls
\f[B]DDC/I2C\f[R] is not a totally reliable form of communication.
VDUs may vary in their responsiveness and compliance.
GPUs, GPU drivers, and types of connection may affect the reliability.
Both ddcutil and vdu_controls attempt to manage the reliability by using
repetition and by adjusting timings.
.PP
If you have the choice, a \f[B]DisplayPort\f[R] to \f[B]DisplayPort\f[R]
connection may be more reliable than \f[B]DVI\f[R] or \f[B]HDMI\f[R].
.PP
Reducing the number of enabled controls can speed up initialization,
decrease the refresh time, and reduce the time taken to restore presets.
.PP
There\(cqs plenty of useful info for getting the best out of
\f[B]ddcutil\f[R] at https://www.ddcutil.com/.
.SS Limitations
.SS Possible impact on VDU lifespan
Repeatably altering VDU settings might affect VDU lifespan, exhausting
the NVRAM write cycles, stressing the VDU power\-supply, or increasing
panel burn\-in.
.PP
That said, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] does include a number of features that
can be used to reduce the overall frequency of adjustments to acceptable
levels.
.IP \(bu 2
Application safeguards:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Slider and spin\-box controls only update the VDU when adjustments
become slow or stop (when no change occurs in 0.5 seconds).
.IP \(bu 2
Where possible, the application only updates VDU values that differ from
its current cached values.
.IP \(bu 2
Automatic ambient brightness adjustment only triggers a change when the
proposed brightness differs from the current brightness by at least 10%.
.IP \(bu 2
The application includes a setter cascade\-guard as a defense against
application, driver, or hardware errors (and cats on keyboards).
If the application or user attempts to set a VDU feature more than 20
times in 65 seconds the application prompts the user for confirmation
before allowing any more setter activity.
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
Usage guidelines:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
When dragging sliders, don\(cqt take lengthy pauses while dragging.
.IP \(bu 2
Choose to restore pre\-prepared `presets' instead of frequently fiddling
with sliders.
.IP \(bu 2
If using the ambient\-light brightness response curves, tune the
settings and curves to minimize frequent small changes.
.IP \(bu 2
If using a light\-meter, disengage metered automatic adjustment when
faced with rapidly fluctuating levels of ambient brightness.
.IP \(bu 2
Consider adjusting the ambient lighting instead of the VDU.
.RE
.IP \(bu 2
Monitoring to assist with making adjustments:
.RS 2
.IP \(bu 2
Hovering over a VDU name in the main window reveals a popup that
includes the number of VCP (NVRAM) writes.
.IP \(bu 2
The bottom of the \f[I]About\-Dialog\f[R] shows the same numbers.
They update dynamically.
.RE
.SS Cross\-platform differences
The UI attempts to step around minor differences between KDE, GNOME, and
the rest, the UI on each may not be exactly the same.
.PP
Depending on which desktop or system\-tray\-extension you are using, a
left\-mouse\-click on the app\-icon in the system\-tray may restore the
application\(cqs main\-window, or it may bring up the application\(cqs
\f[I]main\-menu\f[R].
To support both kinds of desktop, the \f[I]main\-menu\f[R] includes a
\f[I]Control Panel\f[R] menu option that toggles visibility of the main
window.
.PP
Wayland doesn\(cqt allow an application to precisely position its
windows.
When the \f[I]smart\-window\f[R] option is enabled and the desktop
platform is Wayland, the application switches its platform to XWayland
(X11 xcb).
.PP
The scaling and appearance of Qt6 differs from Qt5, its more chunky and
rounded.
If you have Qt5 installed and prefer it, you can uncheck prefer\-qt6 in
settings.
.SS Desktop Theming
Achieving desktop neutrality comes at the price of the application not
being fully aware or compliant with the theming conventions of any
particular desktop.
.PP
For some desktops, Qt can detect in\-session theme changes, such as the
change from a day\-theme to a night\-theme, and the application can
respond appropriately.
For desktops where theme changes aren\(cqt detected, the application can
only conform to the theme detected at startup.
.PP
In some cases, the system\-tray or dock theming may contrast with the
theming applied to windows.
There isn\(cqt a straight forward Qt mechanism to discover whether a
tray or dock is differently themed.
As a result the application includes several manual settings that can
alter the tray/dock icon theming between colored, monochrome\-dark and
monochrome\-light.
.SS Localization
If \f[I]Settings\f[R] → \f[I]translations\f[R] is set, the application
will load a translation matching your system\(cqs locale if available.
.PP
\f[B]The supplied translations are unverified and should be regarded as
samples that may be incorrect.\f[R]
.PP
Where a supported locale is right\-to\-left oriented, layouts will be
reconfigured appropriately.
.PP
Locale is determined by the Linux and Qt environment variables,
\f[B]LC_ALL\f[R] and \f[B]LANGUAGE\f[R], which should preferably be in
agreement.
These two environment variables can be manually set to force a locale,
for example:
.PP
The following locations are searched for localized translations:
.IP "1." 3
\f[B]$HOME/.local/share/vdu_controls/translations/\f[R]
.IP "2." 3
\f[B]/usr/share/vdu_controls/translations/\f[R]
.IP "3." 3
\f[B]zipapp\-root/vdu_controls/resources/translations/\f[R]
.PP
In some cases, Qt internal buttons seem to lack translations in Qt\(cqs
own translation files, either because there isn\(cqt a translation or
&\-shortcut specifiers cause mismatches.
.PD 0
.P
.PD
The \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] code attempts to cope with &\-shortcut
specifier mismatches, but doesn\(cqt include any solutions for
translations that are simply missing.
.PP
To date, there hasn\(cqt been any expression of interest in the
localization features.
The provided translations are all testing samples which may not be
supported over the long term.
.SS Other concerns
The power\-supplies in some older VDUs may buzz/squeel audibly when the
brightness is turned way down.
This may not be a major issue because, in normal surroundings, older
VDUs are often not usable below about 85\-90% brightness.
.PP
Going beyond the standard DDC features by attempting to experiment with
hidden or undocumented features or values has the potential to make
irreversible changes.
.PP
Some controls change the number of connected devices (for example, some
VDUs support a power\-off command).
If such controls are used, \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will detect the change
and will reconfigure the controls for the new situation (for example,
DDC VDU 2 may now be DDC VDU 1).
If you change settings independently of \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R], for
example, by using a VDU\(cqs physical controls, the
\f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] UI includes a refresh button to force it to
assess the new configuration.
.PP
Some VDU settings may disable or enable other settings in the VDU.
For example, setting a VDU to a specific picture\-profile might result
in the contrast\-control being disabled, but \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R] will
not be aware of the restriction resulting in its contrast\-control
erring or appearing to do nothing.
.PP
If your VDUs support \f[I]picture\-modes\f[R], altering any controls in
vdu_controls will most likely result in the picture\-mode being
customized.
For example, say you have selected the VDU\(cqs \f[I]Vivid\f[R]
picture\-mode, if you use vdu_controls to change the brightness, it\(cqs
likely that this will now become the brightness for \f[I]Vivid\f[R]
until the VDU is reset to its defaults.
To avoid confusion, it may be advisable to stick to one picture\-mode
for use with vdu_controls, preserving the others unaltered.
.SS Examples
.IP
.EX
vdu_controls
    All default controls.

vdu_controls \-\-show brightness \-\-show contrast
    Specified controls only:

vdu_controls \-\-hide contrast \-\-hide audio\-volume
    All default controls except for those to be hidden.

vdu_controls \-\-system\-tray \-\-no\-splash \-\-show brightness \-\-show audio\-volume
    Start as a system tray entry without showing the splash\-screen.

vdu_controls \-\-create\-config\-files \-\-system\-tray \-\-no\-splash \-\-show brightness \-\-show audio\-volume
    Create template config files in $HOME/.config/vdu_controls/ that include the other settings.

vdu_controls \-\-enable\-vcp\-code 63 \-\-enable\-vcp\-code 93 \-\-warnings \-\-debug
    All default controls, plus controls for VCP_CODE 63 and 93, show any warnings, output debugging info.
.EE
.PP
This script often refers to displays and monitors as VDUs in order to
disambiguate the noun/verb duality of \(lqdisplay\(rq and
\(lqmonitor\(rq
.SS Prerequisites
Packaged versions of \f[B]vdu_control\f[R] are likely to include all the
following automatically.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]python3\f[R], \f[B]python3\-qt6\f[R] or \f[B]python\-qt5\f[R],
\f[B]noto\-sans\-math\-fonts\f[R],
\f[B]noto\-sans\-symbols2\-fonts\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]ddcutil\f[R], the command line DDC interface.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]libddcutil\f[R] and \f[B]ddcutil\-service\f[R], optional, but
recommended for increased reliability.
more features, and increased speed.
.PP
The following need not be present to run \f[B]vdu_controls\f[R], library
imports are only attempted when settings require them:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]brightnessctl\f[R], optional, needed for controlling
laptop\-panels.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]python3\-pyudev\f[R], optional, needed for detecting brightness
changes on laptop\-panels.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]pyserial\f[R], optional, required to use a serial\-port
light\-metering device (only loaded if needed).
.PP
It\(cqs often best to start simple and get ddcutil working first.
Check that the detect command detects your VDUs without issuing any
errors:
.IP
.EX
    ddcutil detect
.EE
.PP
Read ddcutil documentation concerning config of i2c_dev with Nvidia
GPUs.
Detailed ddcutil info at https://www.ddcutil.com/
.SS Environment
.TP
\f[B]LC_ALL, LANG, LANGUAGE\f[R]
These variables specify the locale for language translations and units of distance. LC_ALL is used by python, LANGUAGE is used by Qt. Normally, they should all have the same value, for example, \f[CR]Da_DK\f[R]. For these to have any effect on language, *Settings* \-> *Translations* must also be enabled.
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_UI_IDLE_SECS\f[R]
The length of pause in slider or spin\-box control motion that triggers commit of the controls value to the VDU. This prevents altering a slider from constantly updating a VDU, which might shorten its NVRAM lifespan. The default is 0.5 seconds.
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_IPINFO_URL\f[R]
Overrides the default ip\-address to location service URL (\f[CR]https://ipinfo.io/json\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_WTTR_URL\f[R]
Overrides the default weather service URL (\f[CR]https://wttr.in\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_WEATHER_KM\f[R]
Overrides the default maximum permissible spherical distance (in kilometres) between the *Settings*\->*Location* and \f[CR]wttr.in\f[R] reported location (\f[CR]200 km\f[R], 124 miles).
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_DDCUTIL_ARGS\f[R]
Add to the list of arguments passed to each exec of ddcutil.
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_DDCUTIL_RETRIES\f[R]
Set the number of times to repeat a ddcutil getvcp or setvcp before returning an error.
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_DBUS_TIMEOUT_MILLIS\f[R]
Dbus call wait timeout. Default is 10000, 10 seconds.
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_DEVELOPER\f[R]
Changes some search paths to include the current working directory, which is more convenient in a development scenario. Enables control of desktop LEDs via brightnessctl so a laptop isn\(aqt required for testing. (\f[CR]no\f[R] or \f[CR]yes\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]VDU_CONTROLS_DEBUG_LAYOUT\f[R]
Draws boxes around the UI elements. (\f[CR]no\f[R] or \f[CR]yes\f[R]).
.SS Files
.TP
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/\f[R]
Location for config files, Presets, and other persistent data.
.TP
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/tray_icon.svg\f[R]
If present, this file is the preferred source for the system\-tray icon. It can be used if the normal icon conflicts with the desktop theme. If the *Settings* *monochrome\-tray* and *mono\-light\-tray* are enabled, they are applied to the file when it is read.
.TP
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls/translations/\f[R]
Location for user supplied translations.
.TP
\f[B]$HOME/.config/vdu_controls.qt.state/\f[R]
Location for Qt/desktop state such as the past window sizes and locations.
.TP
\f[B]/usr/share/vdu_controls\f[R]
Location for system\-wide icons, sample\-scripts, and translations.
